entry.title: [color] Remove BrowserFrame::SelectNativeTheme()
entry.content:
BrowserFrame::SelectNativeTheme() was originally added to support the

BrowserFrame's NativeTheme changing when browser themes were toggled

on/off. This was necessary as themes were painted in light mode, and

if the browser theme was toggled off and the Browser needed to revert

the ColorProviderKey::ColorMode bit, which is independent of the

hierarchy's NativeTheme.

entry.title: [views] Ensure browser theme change notifications propagate to children
entry.content:
Currently browser theme changes are only propagated to the BrowserFrame

root Widget. However currently other owned Widgets in the frame's

hierarchy inherit theme information but will not receive a notification

that this theme information has changed.



This CL ensures that owned Widgets receive ThemeChange() notifications

when the browser theme has changed.



Note: this is not an issue for NativeTheme changes as owned Widgets

maintain their own NativeTheme observations.



This CL also eliminates redundant code in status_bubble_views that

existed to propagate these browser theme change notifications to

the status bubble (which is now covered by the more general change

in this CL).

entry.title: [IP Protection] Improve SetReceiver and Shutdown handling
entry.content:
`IpProtectionAuthTokenProvider::SetReceiver()` can indeed be called when

another receiver has already been set, likely indicating that the

network service crashed. This CL removes the DUMP_WILL_BE_CHECK that

we added to test this.



Also, we didn't previously reset `access_token_fetcher_` in this

case, but I think we should. Otherwise, if it is set, it might

call back into our code after the stored callback has been reset. I

think we also need to reset `access_token_fetcher_` in `Shutdown()`

as well. We pass it our `identity_manager_`, which will become

invalidated after `Shutdown()` is called, so it's probably not safe

for it to stick around after that happens. Because of this, I've

updated how `Shutdown()` works as well, and ensured that at any

async call boundary we do the right thing.

entry.title: Further deflake PDF extension printing tests
entry.content:
The change in https://crrev.com/1183850 helped with reducing flakiness,

but there have still been failures occurring. The fix to wait for the

print job to be released was insufficient, in particular for Windows.

There are cases where a released print job will still be in the pending

state, due to issues in controlled shutdown sequencing.



Resolve this by having the tests wait even longer, until the print job

has been destroyed. Updates related to pending state must be completed

to have gotten to that point.



This change in approach alters how the waiting is done, relying upon

a PrintJob observation instead of one from PrintViewManagerBase. Since

PDF extension tests were the only users of the OnReleasePrintJob()

observation, that can now be removed from PrintViewManagerBase.

entry.title: [ios/sign-in sheet] Re-write account cookie waiting
entry.content:
No behavior change for most practical cases. The CL might also be a

bug fix for some speculative scenarios, more details below.



Context: When accounts.google.com is opened, a bottom sheet is shown

to offer browser sign in. If the user taps its primary button, the

sheet waits until the account cookie is populated, then closes itself.

It might also show an error dialog instead, in case of an auth error or

timeout.



Before this CL, this was implemented as follows:

1. ConsistencyPromoSigninMediator observed the IdentityManager for

its entire lifetime.

2. Upon getting an OnAccountsInCookieUpdated() notification, it

checked whether a) there was no auth error, b) there was a primary

account, and c) the cookie jar was non-empty. If all 3 were

satisfied, it closed the sheet.



This approach has some problems, at least theoretically.

- In 1, more than one notification might arrive. Or a notification

might arrive before the user taps the button.

- In 2, the check is still satisfied if the cookie jar is filled with

an account different from the one selected by the user in the UI.



This CL:

- Extracts the waiting logic to a helper class.

- Checks that cookie jar for the correct account.

entry.title: iwa: StoragePartition::OnClearSiteData to pass StoragePartition along
entry.content:
When StoragePartition::OnClearSiteData() is called, the call

takes the follow route:

> StoragePartition::OnClearSiteData()

> ClearSiteDataHandler::HandleHeader()

> ClearSiteData()

> BrowsingDataRemoverImpl::RemoveWithFilterAndReply()

> StoragePartition::ClearData()



However, any StoragePartition calls OnClearSiteData() will eventually

result in default StoragePartition calling ClearData().



This chain of changes attempts to fix this by passing the

entry.title: [A11y] Ensure that all elements are processed by the AXRelationCache
entry.content:
Previously, our code accidentally skipped processing relations for some elements. This could lead to errors where an aria-owns or other relation was skipped, potentially leading to incorrect or unstable trees.



Now, whenever an object is created in AXObjectCacheImpl::CreateAndInit(), we check to make sure its relations were already processed (they must be processed before creating the AXObject, so that any aria-owns affected parent chain is correct from the start).



In order to satisfy the new stringent checks, the following changes were made:

- Relations are now processed immediately when the node is connected.

- The initial document scan has been improved to traverse nodes connected to shadow roots.

- Relations are registered as soon as possible, rather than waiting for clean layout.



Examples of elements that are now guaranteed to be processed, which previously may not have been:

- Descendants of display:none nodes

- content-visibility:auto or hidden subtrees

- Popup document subtrees



This CL is a prerequisite for a major performance fix in CL:4574033, which needs to know when an element is inside of a label relation, so that tree inclusion can be determined.

Updates how calendar view requests focus for event list close button

after event list gets shown. Adds explicit method to request close

button focus to CalendarEventListView, so CalendarView can use it to

request focus on the close button. This replaces the old logic that

first requested focus on the event list view (which is not focusable),

then advanced focus forward - this would have an effect of moving focus

from the currently focused view to the next view in the focus order,

which worked as intended only if a date cell view had focus.

entry.title: Avoid linker code folding of `__rust_alloc_error_handler`.
entry.content:
Linker code folding of `__rust_alloc_error_handler`:



* Is undesirable (it makes it more difficult to attribute and analyze

crash dumps).

* Has limited benefits in terms of binary-size savings (this is a really

small function).



Based on the above, this CL inserts `NO_CODE_FOLDING()` into the body of

`__rust_alloc_error_handle`.



Note that `NO_CODE_FOLDING` is normally defined in

`//base/debug/alias.h`, but `//build/rust/std` can't depend on

`//base:base` target (because it would lead to cyclical dependencies).

Because of this, the CL duplicates pieces of `//base` into

`//build/rust/std`. For more discussion see a separate bug here:

https://crbug.com/1475734.



Note that this CL doesn't *fix* https://crbug.com/1475734. This CL only

makes it easier to analyze the crash dumps associated with this bug.

entry.title: media: Add secure buffers to VideoDecoderPipeline
entry.content:
Adds handling of secure buffers (when the decoder uses them) to the

VideoDecoderPipeline. This will be used with the ARM V4L2 implementation

of secure playback. The pipeline will request a secure handle from the

decoder (this handle is just an integer specifier, not the actual

resource handle which will be managed by the V4L2Queue). It then

attaches that handle to the DecoderBuffer and performs the Decrypt

operation on it. The secure handle remains with the DecoderBuffer as it

works its way through the rest of the pipeline.



The actual secure buffer (in TrustZone memory) stores the decrypted (or

copied if it's clear) data from the DecoderBuffer for use later in the

secure video decoding process.



This also updates my email address in the OWNERS file to the one I

actually use for reviewing/submitting changes.

entry.title: [UPMLocalPwd] The deletion loading bar finishes displaying
entry.content:
The cause of the problem:

ExportDeletionDialogFragment gets destroyed soon after the user accepts

to delete passwords.

For a larger amount of saved passwords it takes long enough to delete

them so ExportDeletionDialogFragment is destroyed before the callback

that hides the deletion loading bar is executed.



The solution implemented in the CL:

The ExportDeletionDialogFragment doesn't own the loading bar anymore so

it takes a callback to show the loading bar. The sheets coordinator is

in charge of observing the password store and hiding the bar when the

passwords are deleted.
